{
  "answer": "**Chapter 11 of the *Kātyāyana Smṛti* addresses the topic of \"The Representative\" (or legal proxies/pleaders in court).**[^1]\n\nIt outlines rules for appointing representatives by plaintiffs or defendants, who qualifies (e.g., excluding slaves, servants, etc., from fines when acting as pleaders), and restrictions: representatives are prohibited in grave offenses like killing a Brahmin, theft, adultery with a guru's wife, homicide, violence, forgery, and treason, requiring the accused to appear personally.[^2][^3]\n\n[^1]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, Chapter 11 (\"The Representative\"), [paragraph](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/11/translation/#p-08b47b).\n\n[^2]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, Chapter 11, [paragraph](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/11/translation/#p-72c190).\n\n[^3]: Kātyāyana Smṛti, Chapter 11, [paragraph](/works/unknown-katyayana-smrti-1e06d2/11/translation/#p-a0b028).",
